{{Italic title}} {{unreferenced|date=September 2009}} [[Image:BeyondTheMexiqueBay.JPG|thumb|First edition ([[Chatto & Windus]]) ]] '''''Beyond the Mexique Bay''''' is a travel book by [[Aldous Huxley]], first published in 1934. In it, he describes his experiences traveling through the [[Caribbean]] to [[Guatemala]] and southern [[Mexico]] in 1933.
==External links== *[https://archive.org/details/in.ernet.dli.2015.183033 Free download of the book at archive.org]
{{Huxley}}
[[Category:1934 books]] [[Category:Books by Aldous Huxley]] [[Category:British travel books]] [[Category:Books about Mexico]] [[Category:Books about the Caribbean]] [[Category:Chatto & Windus books]] [[Category:English non-fiction books]] {{travel-book-stub}}

'''Daniel Kemmis''' (born c. 1946) is an [[United States|American]]  [[Lawyer|attorney]] and the [[author]] of several books including:

*''Community and the Politics of Place'', University of Oklahoma Press, 1990. {{ISBN|0-8061-2227-7}} ([http://www.fs.fed.us/eco/eco-watch/ew930223 review])
*''The Good City and the Good Life: Renewing the American Community'', Houghton Mifflin, 1995. {{ISBN|0-395-68630-X}}
*''This Sovereign Land: A New Vision for Governing the West'', Island Press, 2001. {{ISBN|1-55963-842-7}}

He was born and raised on a [[farm]] in [[eastern Montana]].  He is a graduate of [[Harvard University]] and the [[University of Montana School of Law]].  He has formerly served as [[mayor]] of [[Missoula, Montana]] (1990–1996), [[Speaker (politics)|speaker]] and [[minority leader]] of the [[Montana House of Representatives]] (1983–1985) and director of the [http://www.crmw.org/ Center for the Rocky Mountain West] at the [[University of Montana]].

In 1995, he was named as one of ''[[Utne Reader]]'s'' 100 Visionaries.<ref name=kemmis>{{cite journal|date=January–February 1995|title=Daniel Kemmis|journal=Utne Reader (online)|url=http://www.utne.com/Politics/Daniel-Kemmis-Personal-Responsibility-Communitarianism.aspx#Kemmis|accessdate=July 26, 2011}}</ref>

He served on the board of directors of [[Philanthropy Northwest]] from 2007 to 2015, representing Montana and the [[Kettering Foundation.]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://philanthropynw.org/search?keys=daniel%20kemmis|website=Philanthropy Northwest|accessdate=24 September 2015}}</ref>

